==English==
===Etymology 1===
Old English [[sugu]].

====Pronunciation====
*[[IPA]]: /saʊ/
*[[SAMPA]]: /<tt>saU</tt>/
*{{audio|en-us-sow-noun.ogg|Audio (US)}}

=====Homophones=====
*[[sough]]

====Noun====
{{en-noun-reg}}

#<!--NPigFemale--> A female [[pig]].
#<!--NIron--> A piece of cast iron produced by a furnace, flat on top, and tapering at each end.
#<!--NWoman-->(''derogatory slang'') A contemptible woman.

=====Quotations=====
*'''1957''': In England, it was generally termed a 'sow', if the weight was above 10 cwts., if below, it was termed a 'pig' from which the present term 'pig iron' is derived. &mdash; H.R. Schubert, ''History of the British Iron and Steel Industry'', p. 160.

=====Synonyms=====
*<!--NWoman-->(''contemptible woman''): [[bitch]], [[cow]]

